<div class="page-header">
  <h1>
    Ember.UI.Panel
    <small>
      <strong>&#123;&#123;#panel&#125;&#125;</strong>...<strong>&#123;&#123;/panel&#125;&#125;</strong>
    </small>
  </h1>
</div>
<p>
  Panels are containers for other views.  A panel is a column, 100% the height of its parent, that
  slides under or over other content.  Typical use cases are left-side menus and right-side property
  panels.
</p>


<hr />
<h3>Appearance</h3>

<h4>Origin and Depth</h4>
<div class="well">
  <div style="width:100%; height:40px; background:#FFF;">
    {{#panel id="panelLeft" depth="below" origin="left" width="240px" style="background:#62c462"}}
    {{/panel}}
    <div style="display:inline-block; position:absolute; width:100%; text-align:center;">
      <img style="height:100%;" src="data:image/jpg;base64,"></img>
    </div>
    {{#panel id="panelRight" depth="above" origin="right" width="240px" style="background:#ee5f5b"}}
    {{/panel}}
  </div>
  <div style="margin-top:20px;">
    {{#button appearance="success" action="toggleLeft" target="controller"}}Toggle Left{{/button}}
    {{#button appearance="danger" action="toggleRight" target="controller"}}Toggle Right{{/button}}
  </div>
</div>
<p>
  By default panels appear from the left side of the screen and seem below other content as in the
  "Toggle Left" example.  The other common appearance is to set the <code>origin</code> to "right"
  and <code>depth</code> to "above" so the panel slides from other side of the screen appearing
  above the main content as in the "Toggle Right" example.  Setting <code>depth</code> to "level"
  removes the drop shadow making the panel appear to have the same depth as the content.
</p>
<pre>&#123;&#123;#panel origin="right" depth="above"&#125;&#125;
  ... Content goes here ...
&#123;&#123;/panel&#125;&#125;</pre>
<br/>

<h4>Width</h4>
<div class="well">
  <div style="width:100%; height:40px; background:#FFF;">
    {{#panel id="panel100" width="100%" style="background:#32394A"}}
    {{/panel}}
  </div>
  <div style="margin-top:20px;">
    {{#button appearance="primary" action="toggle100" target="controller"}}Toggle 100%{{/button}}
  </div>
</div>
<p>
  The <code>width</code> property's default is "320px".  It can be set to a desired width, however,
  panels are never wider than the screen so make sure to test large values on mobile devices.
</p>
<pre>&#123;&#123;#panel width="100%"&#125;&#125;...&#123;&#123;/panel&#125;&#125;</pre>
<br/>

<h4>isOpen</h4>
<div class="well">
  <div style="width:100%; height:40px; background:#FFF;">
    {{#panel isOpen="true" style="background:#32394A"}}
    {{/panel}}
  </div>
</div>
<p>
  Panels are closed by default but that can be changed with the <code>isOpen</code> property.
</p>
<pre>&#123;&#123;#panel isOpen="true"&#125;&#125;...&#123;&#123;/panel&#125;&#125;</pre>


<hr />
<h3>Methods</h3>
<ul>
  <li>
    <code>open([duration], [easing])</code>
    Shows the panel.  Moves other content to make space if needed.
    <ul>
      <li class="unstyled">
        <code>duration</code> is an optional parameter for the length of the panel slide animation
        in milliseconds.  The default is 200 (milliseconds).
      </li>
      <li>
        <code>easing</code> is an optional parameter defining the easing function for the animation.
        The default is 'swing', 'linear' is possible,
        <a href="http://jqueryui.com/resources/demos/effect/easing.html">others are available with
        jQuery UI</a>.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>
    <code>close([duration], [easing])</code>
    Hides the panel.  Other content will typically move to occupy the forfeited space (depending on
    CSS).
  </li>
  <li>
    <code>toggle([duration], [easing])</code>
    Hides the panel if it visible; otherwise shows the panel.
  </li>
</ul>
<br/>

<h4>Example</h4>
<p>
  Adding a close button on a panel:
</p>
<pre>&#123;&#123;#panel id="menuPanel"&#125;&#125;
  ...
  &#123;&#123;#button action="close" target="controller"&#125;&#125;Close&#123;&#123;/button&#125;&#125;
  ...
&#123;&#123;/panel&#125;&#125;</pre>
<pre>close: function() {
  var menuPanel = Ember.View.views['menuPanel'];
  menuPanel.close();
}</pre>
